e countered. A compelling work of intellectual history, John Adams and the Fear of American Oligarchy has important lessons for today’s world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aOligarchyzUnited States. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAlexis de Tocqueville.  aAmerican enlightenment.  aAnglomanes.  aDiscourses on Davila.  aEnglish-style government.  aFrench Revolution.  aJohn Adams.  aJohn Taylor of Caroline.  aMary Wollstonecraft.  aScottish Enlightenment.  aThomas Jefferson.  aUS Constitution.  aUS government.  aUSn government.  aaristocracy.  aaristocratic power.  abalanced government.  aconstitutional model.  ademocracy.  ainequality.  aoligarchy.  apolitical elites.  apolitical influence.  apolitical power.  apolitical thought.  apublic admiration.  arepublican America.  awealth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831106633650 cprintz978069117153140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691184456?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691184456423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691184456/original  a978-3-11-066336-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles